content.description: Long and powerful moves at the bottom are followed by some easier climbing.  However, the crux is near the top of this nearly vertical climb.
content.location: The third bolted line from the RIGHT hand side of the cliff.  This is the fourth bolted line to the right of Joint Checking.  Both Twins and Wing Walker can be seen from the same location.  Wing Walker is left of Twins, and the bottom bolts are spaced farther apart.

content.description: The route consists of two cruxes with good climbing between the cruxes.  The first crux comes at the bottom and consists of a dyno or high step and a right angling hand traverse.  The upper crux is on thin holds around the last two bolts.
content.protection: Bolts to a two bolt anchor.
content.location: Second sport climb from the RIGHT hand side of the cliff.  There are two sport climbs which start right next to eachother.  The left one is Wing Walker and the right one is Twins.

content.description: Steep climbing at the start to a large ledge.  From the ledge go straight up on thin holds to large pockets and a somewhat runout but easy finish.
content.protection: 7(?) bolts and a two bolt anchor.
content.location: The fourth route to the right of the drainage, which is the first route to the right of Katy's Trail.

content.description: A one move crux at the bottom is followed by some much easier climbing.  However, there are many loose blocks and loose rock to the anchors.
content.protection: bolts to a two bolt anchor.
content.location: The last line on the right side of the cliff line.  There is a steep gully just past the cliff.

content.description: The first route established on the cliff.  Climb the bottom on some interesting 5.11 climbing past a lieback and go left to a large ledge and rest.  The crux comes off the ledge, then the route trends right to a two bolt anchor.  A direct version avoids the rest and takes a more difficult line straight up.
content.protection: Bolts to a two bolt anchor.  The first bolt appears to be a little rusty from the ground.
content.location: The third sport route to the right of the drainage.

content.description: A very tricky move gets you off the ground.  This move of faith is followed by interesting and continually powerful climbing to the finish.  Remember that your gear is only as good as the rock it is placed in.
content.protection: Bolts and a mid sized cam to a two bolt anchor.
content.location: Sixth route to the right of the drainage.  This is the first route to the right of the large rock "throne" that is usually at the base of the cliff.

content.description:
From MO' Beta by Jer Collins:

 "The old adage rings true: the better the rock quality, the harder the climbing. Perfect rock makes this line pretty tough."

 Bolts right of Psychiatry Kills. Looks blank.

Start with some long reaches around the first bolt to an interesting crux by the fourth bolt.  The crux can be done either by going straight up past the bolt, or by going out left then doing some big moves to come back right at the fifth bolt.
content.protection: 5 bolts and a two bolt anchor.
content.location: The first route to the right of the drainage.  The farthest route to the left on the cliff.

content.protection: 5 bolts. One bolt has an oldish perma on it.
content.location: Starts in broken rock and ends (IIRC) under a roof.

content.description: Direct version of Katy's Trail. After the initial boulder problem head directly up instead of left. Small holds, cruxy.
content.protection: 5 bolts or so. Chain anchor, there may be a 'biner or two up there.
content.location: Shares a start with Katy's Trail

content.description: Mostly sport climbs on good quality rock for mid-Missouri.
